deck: Bi-annual volume of Oor Wullie's escapades
description: DC Thomson annuals featuring mischievous Scottish lad Oor Wullie, created by Robert Duncan Low and Dudley Watkins for the Sunday Post newspaper's Fun Section in 1936. The first annual came out in 1940 (catalogued as 1941), and alternated with Low and Watkins' The Broons thereafter, with Wullie annuals on even years and Broons on odd. The second Oor Wullie collection came out in 1942, but wartime paper shortages forced DC Thomson to skip producing Oor Wullie collections in 1944 and 1946. They resumed in 1947 (for the Broons) and 1948 (for Oor Wullie), and have come out every two years since.
name: Oor Wullie

description:
Speed was launched on 23rd February 1980, a new boys' comic from IPC. Speed lasted 31 unnumbered issues, missing several weeks due to industrial action (there were no issues published between the 17th May and 28th June issues, a gap of 6 weeks) and cancelling on 25th October 1980. It merged with Tiger a week later.

Note: Because issues were unnumbered, they are listed below by month, date. Since all Speed issues came out in 1980, the year isn't included in the numbering here.
name: Speed

description: Mon Journal's Janus Stark presented French translations of a number of British and Italian adventure strips. Each issue of Janus Stark was split into three stories, each reprinting as many as thirty-five pages of foreign material. Since British strips tended to average at no more than three pages per episode, this meant that the French reprints burned through the equivalent of up to twelve U.K. episodes per issue, and as a result most back up strips didn't last beyond a few issues, though Adam Eterno, Buster's Leopard From Lime Street and Speed / Tiger's Death Wish proved exceptions, as each had lengthy U.K. runs available to translate. However, Stark himself proved so popular that when Mon Journal ran out of existing stories from the English titles Stark had appeared in after 36 issues they hired the creators to produce new Janus Stark adventures for them. In issue 89 the series ended and the next issue a run of reprints of earlier Janus Stark adventures began, ending with issue 125. For the final ten issues of the series Janus Stark no longer appeared in the series, despite his name providing the title; instead Mandrake the Magician became the lead feature. The comic ended with issue 135.
name: Janus Stark

deck: Collection of old British comic strips
description:
An oddity for British comics, The Giant Holiday Fantasy Comic Album (and its sister volumes, The Giant Holiday Adventure Comic Album, Giant Holiday All-Girl Comic Album and Giant Holiday Fun Comic Album) collected an unusual range of old IPC-owned comic strips from several different defunct titles and reprinted them together to form a massive 288 page cheaply-priced black and white volume not dissimilar to the later Marvel Essentials line. It was edited and compiled by Mike Higgs, and published by Hawk Books.

This volume, as the name suggests, concentrated mainly on strips with a fantasy element to them, though fantasy was used loosely and included science-fiction tales. The individual stories varied widely in length, as Higgs reprinted complete storylines - thus, some strips were only a couple of pages long, as compared to, for example, the Steel Claw, which takes up over 90 pages to reprint "The Return of the Claw" storyline.
name: Giant Holiday Fantasy Comic Album

It was edited and compiled by Mike Higgs, and published by Hawk Books.

This volume, as the name suggests, concentrated mainly on adventure strips.
